"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059920","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-02-20","<p>Since the Prime Minister met President Juncker on 7 February to begin discussions on how we can address the concerns of Parliament, their respective teams have been holding talks to find a way forward that will work for both sides. She is also continuing engagement with the leaders of the other EU member states, including the Taoiseach.</p><p>Her message to those leaders, and to the leaders of the EU institutions, is the same: the UK wants to leave the EU as scheduled on 29 March with a guarantee that there will be no hard border in Northern Ireland, there is a majority in Parliament for a revised Withdrawal Agreement, and we need legally-binding changes to the backstop in order to secure that majority.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2019-02-20T17:37:24.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059920/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059920/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-02-12","Brexit: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with his Irish counterpart on the Malthouse alternative plan for the backstop.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","220163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059921","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-02-18","<p>The Secretary of State meets regularly with EU counterparts to discuss issues related to our exit.</p><p>The Political Declaration makes clear that both the EU and the UK will aim to provide visa-free travel for short-term visits as part of our future relationship.</p><p>The European Commission proposed to grant UK nationals visa-free travel to the EU, even in the event of a no deal, subject to reciprocity from the UK. This proposal is currently passing through the EU’s legislative process. This would mean that UK nationals would not need a visa when travelling to the Schengen area for short stays of up to 90 days in every 180-day period. The UK has also said that we do not intend to require visas for tourists from the EU.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2019-02-18T12:23:32.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059921/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059921/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-02-12","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent discussions he has had with his EU counterparts on visa-free holiday trips for (a) UK citizens to their countries and (b) citizens of EU countries to the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","220164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059923","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-02-18","<p>The Prime Minister retains personal overall responsibility for the negotiations on the UK side and is supported by her Europe Advisor, who heads up the official-level negotiating team.</p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-02-18T09:54:05.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059923/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059923/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-02-12","Oliver Robbins","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what position in the hierarchy of negotiators Olly Robbins holds.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","220165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059924","Department for Transport","false","2019-02-20","<p>The Secretary of State and officials from the Department have and will continue to engage with stakeholders from across the aviation industry on all issues relating to EU Exit.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-02-20T11:32:39.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059924/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059924/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-02-12","Aviation: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with airlines on additional charges to fly from the UK to EU member states after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","220166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059925","Cabinet Office","false","2019-02-18","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2019-02-18T14:14:00.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059925/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059925/answer","PQ220269 - Uploaded.pdf","UKSA Response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059925/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-02-12","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what method his Department uses to record multinational intra-company transfers.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","220296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059926","Department for Transport","false","2019-02-20","<p>Customer satisfaction is an absolute priority for the Department. In rail, we are investing £48 billion to help modernise the network and deliver significant improvements in performance, punctuality and capacity across the country. We are upgrading the East Coast and Great Western Mainlines and introducing brand new trains across the network with orders for over 7,800 new carriages placed since 2010. We have also introduced new measures on compensation, an independent rail ombudsman and commissioned an independent root and branch review of the railway.</p><p> </p><p>Buses already enjoy high customer satisfaction with the latest Transport Focus Bus Passenger Survey revealing that almost nine out of ten passengers saying they are satisfied with their bus service. The Bus Services Act 2017 introduced a number of new tools to help local authorities improve local bus services. Through partnership arrangements we have enabled local authorities and bus operators to work constructively to provide better services for passengers.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-02-20T16:35:57.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059926/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059926/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-02-12","Public Transport: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to increase customer satisfaction in (a) rail and (b) other forms of public transport.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","220167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059927","Department for Transport","false","2019-02-20","<p>In regard to rail, the Government regulates around one third of all rail fares to protect passengers that rely on trains to get to work from high fare rises. Since 2014, these regulated fares have been capped at inflation.</p><p> </p><p>We want fares to be linked to the more commonly used CPI measure of inflation in the future but, to be sustainable, income and costs to the rail industry, including staffing costs, must change in parallel. The Secretary of State has therefore written to the rail industry and the unions, asking for their help to move rail from RPI to CPI, to reduce costs so that savings can be passed on to passengers.</p><p> </p><p>In regard to buses, in order to mitigate fare increases the Government provides £250 million to support bus services through the Bus Service Operators Grant, with £43 million paid directly to local authorities. In real terms, annual total net support for bus services since 2010/11 has averaged 23 percent more than in the 1996/97 to 2009/10 period.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-02-20T16:00:01.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059927/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059927/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-02-12","Public Transport: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he is taking steps to prevent continual fare increases in public transport; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","220168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059928","Department for Transport","false","2019-02-20","<p>All drivers must renew their driving entitlement when they reach the age of 70 and at most every three years after that. This provides a timely reminder to individuals to consider their health in the context of driving. To renew their entitlement, drivers must make a legal declaration that they can meet the required standards and confirm whether they have any listed medical condition. Drivers who advise the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency of a relevant medical condition will be investigated and a driving licence will only be issued if they can meet the appropriate health standards.</p><p> </p><p>The Department announced in June 2018 that it has identified older people as one of four priority road user groups which will be included in the forthcoming Road Safety statement and action plan.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-02-20T12:30:56.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059928/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059928/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-02-12","Driving: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that older drivers are fit to drive.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","220169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059930","Department for Transport","false","2019-02-20","<p>Ministers have regular discussions with car manufacturers on a range of issues, including the market for ultra low and zero emission vehicles. The Road to Zero strategy, published in July 2018, sets out the Government’s plans to support the transition to zero emission vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is investing nearly £1.5bn between April 2015 and March 2021, with grants available for plug in vehicles and schemes to support chargepoint infrastructure. Along with the measures in the Government’s strategy, this adds up to one of the most comprehensive support packages in the world.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-02-20T12:24:51.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059930/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059930/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-02-12","Electric Vehicles: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with car manufacturers on the cost of hybrid and electric cars in the UK and incentives to encourage consumers to buy more eco-friendly vehicles.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","220170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059931","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-20","<p>On 24 July 2018, the government published the provisional findings of the trade remedies call for evidence into which existing EU measures will be transitioned. The provisional findings indicate the measures on aluminium foil will be terminated when the UK leaves the EU. No UK producer responded to the call for evidence</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/call-for-evidence-to-identify-uk-interest-in-existing-eu-trade-remedy-measures" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/call-for-evidence-to-identify-uk-interest-in-existing-eu-trade-remedy-measures</a><br> Since then, UK producers and interested parties were invited to provide further information which may affect these findings. The government is in the final stages of considering additional information from industry, and will publish the final report shortly.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2019-02-20T11:17:55.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059931/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059931/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059931/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-02-12","Antidumping Duties: Aluminium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2018 to Question 177208 on Antidumping Duties: Aluminium, when his Department plans to publish the final report on the trade remedies call for evidence into which existing EU measures will be transitioned once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","220133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059932","Wales Office","false","2019-02-18","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Bill is an essential part of our preparations for a smooth and orderly exit from the EU. The Bill is yet to be introduced, but we expect to seek the legislative consent of the National Assembly for Wales for some of its provisions.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government has undertaken extensive and meaningful engagement with the Welsh Government in preparing the Bill. Regular JMC (European Negotiations) meetings have provided a productive forum for Ministers from the UK, Welsh and Scottish governments to discuss the Bill. The UK Government has also shared clauses in draft with Ministers from the devolved administrations, allowing them the opportunity to comment and inform the UK Government’s approach to the Bill. UK Government officials have also met with their counterparts in the Welsh Government on a fortnightly basis since the summer to discuss the Bill. The Welsh Government has been positive about both the quantity and quality of engagement to date and this engagement will continue as we prepare for the introduction of the Bill.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","220304","2019-02-18T10:52:41.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059932/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059932/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2019-02-12","Brexit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether the European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Bill will require a legislative consent motion from the National Assembly for Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","220303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059934","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-20","<p>On 24 July 2018, the government published the provisional findings of the trade remedies call for evidence into which existing EU measures will be transitioned. The provisional findings indicate the measures on aluminium foil will be terminated when the UK leaves the EU. No UK producer responded to the call for evidence</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/call-for-evidence-to-identify-uk-interest-in-existing-eu-trade-remedy-measures" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/call-for-evidence-to-identify-uk-interest-in-existing-eu-trade-remedy-measures</a><br> Since then, UK producers and interested parties were invited to provide further information which may affect these findings. The government is in the final stages of considering additional information from industry, and will publish the final report shortly.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2019-02-20T11:18:26.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059934/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059934/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-02-12","Antidumping Duties: Aluminium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2018 to Question 117208 on Anti-dumping Duties: Aluminium, what recent steps he has taken to ensure that anti-dumping duties on aluminium foil will be maintained after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","220134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059935","Wales Office","false","2019-02-18","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Bill is an essential part of our preparations for a smooth and orderly exit from the EU. The Bill is yet to be introduced, but we expect to seek the legislative consent of the National Assembly for Wales for some of its provisions.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government has undertaken extensive and meaningful engagement with the Welsh Government in preparing the Bill. Regular JMC (European Negotiations) meetings have provided a productive forum for Ministers from the UK, Welsh and Scottish governments to discuss the Bill. The UK Government has also shared clauses in draft with Ministers from the devolved administrations, allowing them the opportunity to comment and inform the UK Government’s approach to the Bill. UK Government officials have also met with their counterparts in the Welsh Government on a fortnightly basis since the summer to discuss the Bill. The Welsh Government has been positive about both the quantity and quality of engagement to date and this engagement will continue as we prepare for the introduction of the Bill.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","220303","2019-02-18T10:52:42.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059935/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059935/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2019-02-12","Brexit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps he has taken to ensure that the Government receives legislative consent from the National Assembly for Wales on the European Union (Withdrawal Agreement) Bill.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","220304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059936","Treasury","false","2019-02-19","<p>No assessment of the Exchequer impact of reducing the rate of Pool Betting Duty to 10% has been made.</p><p> </p><p>However due to the ease of changing between pools betting and regular betting the Government considers it would put a significant portion of the General Betting Duty receipts at risk – which totalled £572m in 2017-18.</p><p> </p><p>A list of current and future gambling duty rates can be found in Annex A of the Government’s Budget 2018 document.</p><p> </p><p>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/754766/Annex_A_rates_and_allowances.pdf</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","220075 ; 220076","2019-02-19T12:48:59.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059936/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1059936/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-02-12","Football Pools: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to Answer of 29 January 2019 to Question 210669, what would be the net cost to the public purse of reducing the football pools betting duty from 15 to 10 per cent.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","220074"
